    "keyframes": [
        {
            "Text": "What you're seeing is a year's worth of fires on Earth between April 2016 and March 2017 from a satellite with infrared (heat) sensors. Depending on where you are on Earth, you will see different sorts of fires.",
            "BoundingBox": {
                "ne": {"lat": 80.68488817791945, "lng": -224.97899500878628},
                "sw": {"lat": -67.90579595557553, "lng": 222.51849592182208}
            },
            "Pause": false,
            "StartFrame": "2016-04-01",
            "Layers": [
                "show-viirs"
            ],
            "Map": "dark-base"
        },

        {
            "Text": "What you're seeing here is not the ocean on fire around South America but rather what's known as the South Atlantic Anomaly. The Earth is surrounded by a pair of concentric donut-shaped clouds called the Van Allen radiation belts, which interfere with satellite equipment and produce \"glitches\" in the data.",
            "BoundingBox": {
                "ne":{"lat":21.624029563161002,"lng":-124.61630961529137},"sw":{"lat":-50.58961292225278,"lng":28.129865864127026}
            },
            "Pause": false,
            "Layers": [
                "show-viirs"
            ],
            "Map": "dark-base"
        },

        {
            "Text": "If you look closely though you can still see some consistent, bright lights. These are the result of offshore drilling.",
            "BoundingBox": {
                "ne":{"lat":-8.215127792571,"lng":-66.3035319165857},"sw":{"lat":-35.759420277697615,"lng":-9.54698008519972}
            },
            "Pause": false,
            "Layers": [
                "show-viirs"
            ],
            "Map": "dark-base"
        },

        {
            "Text": "In Africa, seasonal fires occur during the winter and in early spring every year. North and south of the equator, people burn fields to bring back tender grass for grazing or to ready fields for farming.",
            "BoundingBox": {
                "ne":{"lat":55.973611032181516,"lng":-97.26372326956887},"sw":{"lat":-46.243161338047734,"lng":129.30345413711572}
            },
            "Pause": false,
            "Layers": [
                "show-viirs"
            ],
            "Map": "dark-base"
        },


        {
            "Text": "In northern Africa and the Middle East, the fires you're seeing tend to come from oil extraction. Oil extraction occurs all across the planet. People take oil out of the ground and then flare the methane that comes with the oil. This flaring of methane results in these long lasting fires that appear to burn all year round.",
            "BoundingBox": {
                "ne":{"lat":47.14119311321615,"lng":-5.373883938156126},"sw":{"lat":8.913287631201014,"lng":78.81265433301658}
            },
            "Pause": false,
            "Layers": [
                "show-viirs"
            ],
            "Map": "dark-base"
        },
        {
            "Text": "In the United States we see examples of bright white lights visible from space, representing high fire intensity and concentration. Notice the perpetually burning fires in North Dakota and Texas. These fires are the result of hydraulic fracturing.",
            "BoundingBox": {
                "ne":{"lat":54.17951535208853,"lng":-131.2652514276748},"sw":{"lat":24.493882035313515,"lng":-56.87802621126659}
            },
            "Pause": false,
            "Layers": [
                "show-viirs"
            ],
            "Map": "dark-base"
        },
        {
            "Text": "Hydraulic fracturing or \"fracking\" is a process for obtaining natural gases from the ground. \"Fracking\" involves pumping large amounts of water, sand, and chemicals into the ground in order to break apart the rock to release natural gas. (For Pittsburgh residents, if you've ever seen the big oil trains come through, about a quarter of the oil from North Dakota comes through Pittsburgh on the way to refinement in Philadelphia.)",
            "BoundingBox": {
                "ne":{"lat":54.17951535208853,"lng":-131.2652514276748},"sw":{"lat":24.493882035313515,"lng":-56.87802621126659}
            },
            "Pause": false,
            "Layers": [
                "show-viirs"
            ],
            "Map": "dark-base"
        },
        {
            "Text": "The Bakken Shale formation in North Dakota is one of the top oil-producing regions in the United States and natural gas production there has more than doubled since 2005.",
            "BoundingBox": {
                "ne":{"lat":51.79044232846596,"lng":-112.65714230827193},"sw":{"lat":43.05806197685102,"lng":-88.23410213655207}
            },
            "Pause": false,
            "Layers": [
                "show-viirs"
            ],
            "Map": "dark-base"
        },
        {
            "Text": "Due to insufficient infrastructure, over one-third of North Dakota's natural gas production is flared or otherwise not marketed. It is generally better to flare natural gas than to vent it into the atmosphere because methane, a primary component of natural gas, is a much more powerful greenhouse gas than carbon dioxide.",
            "BoundingBox": {
                "ne":{"lat":51.79044232846596,"lng":-112.65714230827193},"sw":{"lat":43.05806197685102,"lng":-88.23410213655207}
            },
            "Pause": false,
            "Layers": [
                "show-viirs"
            ],
            "Map": "dark-base"
        },
        {
            "Text": "In California, forest fires are becoming more prevalent as a result of a warmer, drier summers with little rainfall. Look for very bright flashes of light, representing these fires.",
            "BoundingBox": {
                "ne":{"lat":42.73466859375439,"lng":-133.00747992147862},"sw":{"lat":31.057874672431897,"lng":-105.36709946457522}
            },
            "Pause": false,
            "Layers": [
                "show-viirs"
            ],
            "Map": "dark-base"
        },
        {
            "Text": "From June to October 2015, fires destroyed 6.4 million acres of forest throughout Indonesia and brought about an air pollution crisis. The fires, resulting from illegal slash-and-burn practices, spread quickly during the dry season. Draining and conversion of peatland, driven by the expansion of palm oil plantations, contributed to the intensity of haze from the fires.",
            "BoundingBox": {
                "ne":{"lat":9.77890318744266,"lng":82.82748412788706},"sw":{"lat":-10.069828090516134,"lng":120.45194077842817}
            },
